    <title>Combined summary - Adding New BIP Editors</title>
    <updated>2024-04-08T01:59:59.312931+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CAMHHROw9mZJRnTbUo76PdqwJU==YJMvd9Qrst+nmyypaedYZgg@mail.gmail.com/T/#m00da3eebfae756f3f6b8991fa5645510458cbe56" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin development community is actively engaging in discussions to refine the governance and improve the efficiency of the Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs) process. Recognizing the need for enhanced documentation quality and decision-making, the proposal to include seasoned contributors such as Murch, Ruben Kanzure, Jon Atack, et al. into the BIP editorial team is intended to leverage their technical expertise. This initiative aims at incorporating key contributors into pivotal roles to foster a dynamic leadership structure, thereby aligning with the broader goal of strengthening the Bitcoin development ecosystem.

There is an emphasis on diversifying perspectives within the BIP editorial process and adopting a practical approach towards proposal evaluation. The ongoing dialogue touches upon procedural aspects such as criteria for acceptance, classification of proposals, and mechanisms like a "Discussion" header to facilitate tracking proposal development. Additionally, refining the acceptance criteria based on formatting, editorial quality, and relevance to technologies supporting Bitcoin is highlighted as crucial for ensuring a fair and consistent review process.

Operational challenges within the BIP framework, including the limited availability of current editors and concerns over attempts to bypass the established process, are being addressed. Proposals to broaden the editor group to reflect majority consensus and enhance transparency in procedural aspects are discussed. Furthermore, adopting methodologies similar to those used by the IETF for managing standards and selecting new BIP editors for broad support are suggested to ensure equality among editors and streamline the proposal numbering process.

Moreover, the necessity for more BIP editors to alleviate delays in assigning numbers and merging approved changes is acknowledged, alongside considerations for modifying the governance structure. Suggestions include archiving the current unified BIPs repository in favor of decentralized individual repositories, while still valuing the unified repository's accessibility. Separating the roles of mailing list moderators and BIP editors is proposed to maintain impartiality.

The role of BIP editor is critical for maintaining the quality and coherence of proposals, requiring not only grammatical and stylistic proficiency but also a deep understanding of the technology and a commitment to decentralization and innovation. Luke Dashjr's potential responsibility for appointing new BIP editors and the endorsement of specific individuals for the role based on their unique strengths are noted. However, concerns regarding certain candidates' suitability due to their approach or lack of interest in understanding technical decisions' historical rationale are raised.

A proposal suggests shifting the responsibility of assessing technical soundness from BIP editors to the broader community, focusing on submissions' relevance to the Bitcoin ecosystem and adherence to formal criteria. This approach aims to expedite the review process by involving direct contact with authors and following specific guidelines in the BIP documentation.

These discussions and proposals represent a concerted effort within the Bitcoin development community to address the current challenges facing the BIP process. By exploring ways to enhance workflow efficiency, governance, and the overall review process, the community seeks to streamline the development and improvement of the Bitcoin protocol, reflecting a commitment to guiding its future in a thoughtful and inclusive manner.</summary>
